Movie Ratings & User Behavior Analysis

Name: Masudi Hamisi
Student ID: 676797
Course: DSA1080A – Programming for Data Science

1. Introduction

This project analyzes movie ratings using the MovieLens dataset. The aim is to understand how users rate movies and identify patterns in popularity and ratings.

Movie data analysis is important because it helps understand user preferences and can be used in recommendation systems like Netflix.

The main goals of this project are:

To analyze movie ratings
To identify popular and highly rated movies
To study trends over time
To understand the relationship between ratings and popularity

2. Dataset

The dataset used in this project comes from MovieLens and includes several files:

movies_metadata.csv
ratings_small.csv
links.csv
keywords.csv
credits.csv

After merging, the dataset had:

45433 rows
35+ columns

3. Data Cleaning

Before analysis, the data was cleaned to remove errors.

The following steps were done:

Removed missing values
Converted data types (dates, IDs)
Merged datasets using movieId
Removed duplicates
Converted release_date to datetime

New columns created:

avg_rating
rating_count
year
age

The cleaned dataset was saved as:
cleaned_movies_dataset.csv

4. Data Analysis
4.1 Summary Statistics

Most movies have average ratings between 3 and 4, meaning users usually give moderate ratings.

4.2 Top Rated Movies

The top-rated movies were identified using average rating. These movies have the highest scores but may not always be popular.

4.3 Most Popular Movies

The most popular movies were identified using the number of ratings. These movies have been rated by many users.

4.4 Movies Over Time

The number of movies released has increased over the years. This shows growth in the film industry.

4.5 Ratings vs Popularity

Movies with few ratings can have very high or very low scores.
Movies with many ratings usually have stable scores.

5. Advanced Analysis
5.1 Old vs New Movies

Movies were divided into:
Old movies
New movies

Older movies tend to have slightly higher ratings.

5.2 Correlation

The relationship between rating_count and avg_rating is weak.
This means popularity does not strongly affect ratings.

5.3 Director Analysis

Some directors consistently have higher-rated movies compared to others.

6. Key Insights
Most movies have moderate ratings
Popular movies have more stable ratings
Highly rated movies are not always popular
Movies with few ratings are less reliable
Older movies often have slightly higher ratings

7. Recommendations
Use movies with many ratings for reliable analysis
Promote highly rated but less popular movies
Analyze genres and keywords for deeper insights

8. Conclusion

This project analyzed movie ratings and user behavior using the MovieLens dataset. The results show that ratings are generally stable and that popularity does not strongly affect ratings.

The project also shows the importance of cleaning data and using proper analysis methods.

